<section id="design">
  <h2>Platform &amp; Build Quality</h2>
  <p>LeadsMiner Pro is a desktop application, not a browser extension or web-based dashboard. Third-party walkthroughs consistently describe it as a downloadable Windows and Mac application that users install on their own machine, then connect to their personal Facebook account via in-app setup. This is a different architecture from web-based tools and means the software is running directly on the user's device, interacting with Facebook through the user's login session.</p>

  <h3>Installation and Access</h3>
  <p>Based on publicly available descriptions, access works as follows: after purchase, the buyer receives login credentials and a download link via email, downloads the appropriate installer for their operating system, runs the installer, and then follows an in-app tutorial to connect the software to their Facebook account. The installation process is described across multiple third-party reviews as beginner-friendly, taking around three to five minutes.</p>

  <h3>Trust Signals and Concerns</h3>
  <p>The official site leadsminerpro.com is listed as the primary sales destination. The product has a standard MunchEye launch listing, which places it squarely in the info-product and software-launch ecosystem. We could not verify the depth or quality of the member dashboard, post-purchase support, or update cadence first-hand.</p>

  <h3>Long-Term Considerations</h3>
  <p>Desktop automation tools that interact directly with Facebook via a user's login session — rather than through Meta's official API — face a structural fragility: Facebook regularly updates its platform and its detection of automated activity, which can render tools of this type non-functional without warning, or trigger account restrictions on users running them. This is not a risk unique to LeadsMiner Pro; it is a category-level risk for all Facebook automation software that does not hold official Meta partner status.</p>
</section>

