  <h3>4.2 Key Performance Categories</h3>

  <h4>Lead Generation Potential</h4>
  <p>The underlying concept — identifying people already engaging in your niche on Facebook and reaching out to them directly — is a sound organic prospecting strategy when done by hand. Whether automation meaningfully improves outcomes over manual outreach, or at what volume the tool operates effectively, is not independently verified. The "28% reply rate" figure cited in some marketing materials is not sourced to any audited study or independently published data.</p>

  <h4>Facebook Terms of Service and Account Safety</h4>
  <Callout type="warn">
    <strong>This is the central risk most marketing materials understate:</strong> Facebook's Terms of Service prohibit automated activity — including automated friend requests — unless the tool uses Meta's officially authorized API. LeadsMiner Pro is not listed as an authorized Meta partner or API integration. It operates as a desktop application that simulates user actions directly. Facebook actively detects and penalises this category of automation, and consequences range from temporary action limits to permanent account termination. The marketing claims the tool "respects daily limits," but rate-limiting is not the same as being platform-authorized. Any prospective buyer should evaluate this risk independently and consider testing only on a secondary account.
  </Callout>

  <h4>Income and Results Claims</h4>
  <Callout type="warn">
    <strong>Why we are cautious here:</strong> Marketing materials cite Wayne Crowe generating "$140,000 in sales" using this method. This figure is self-reported by the product creator, appears across multiple promotional pages, and has not been independently audited. No independently verified data on what a typical LeadsMiner Pro user earns — or whether they recover the cost of the software — exists in publicly available sources. Income figures from third-party reviewers are similarly self-reported and originate from people promoting the product via their own referral links.
  </Callout>

  <h4>Community and Support</h4>
  <p>Support is described as live Facebook sessions with Wayne Crowe (reportedly two to three per week) plus onboarding training videos. There is no indication of a formal one-on-one support channel or a ticketed help desk beyond what is described in marketing materials.</p>
</section>

<section id="ux">
  <h2>User Experience</h2>
  <h3>Setup Process</h3>
  <p>Third-party walkthroughs describe a short setup flow: purchase, receive download credentials by email, download and install the Windows or Mac application, and connect the software to a Facebook account using in-app tutorial guidance. Setup is consistently described as taking under ten minutes for someone with basic computer skills.</p>
  <h3>Daily Usage</h3>
  <p>Ongoing use centres on configuring keyword or group targets, running the Post Friender or Member Friender tools within the software's stated daily limits, and then following up separately with newly added connections — either manually or using the Mass Messenger add-on. The software does not manage any follow-up communication automatically in the front-end version.</p>
  <h3>Learning Curve</h3>
  <p>Multiple reviewers describe the interface as beginner-friendly with a point-and-click layout. However, getting meaningful results from the tool requires choosing effective niche keywords or groups to target, understanding how many friend requests per day to send without triggering Facebook's anomaly detection, and having a follow-up strategy ready once connections are made. None of these decisions are made for the user by the software.</p>
  <h3>Interface and Usability</h3>
  <p>We could not verify the interface first-hand. Third-party walkthrough videos describe separate panels for each core tool (Post Friender, Member Friender, Audience Builder) within a single desktop application. As noted throughout, the reviewers who produced these walkthroughs are affiliate promoters, not independent evaluators.</p>
</section>

